Tv7XNPaw-LFvqSi2AfltgAUOcEoG-M-kkgKJUhdrSMuQpGj-LcJyRwirTIFgsTvPM75OV7ntgHU3WmNIk25Bs7BGpgM7Owwcb4yBC5DNWGkNYYCQLeRMhfkVy5lymkPVHZDu44=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing test coverage**\\n\\nI need to figure out the coverage issue. I'm considering if a package-private static method means invocations through reflection could also be tested dynamically. Maybe the JUnit native test only ran the native image? The command reports tests completed, suggesting the JVM passed. However, coverage might not be reflecting accurately after the external workflow. It seems like direct private reflection isn’t sufficient, especially if the native image call isn't instrumented correctly. I’ll need to inspect the dynamic access report further.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring coverage filtering**\\n\\nI’m wondering if the coverage system is filtering out Class.forName when called from a method invoked reflectively. It seems like the dynamic agent could be recording the caller incorrectly. Perhaps the stack frame is missing? If closureClass() fails with MethodHandles, then maybe the class$ is not accessed correctly. I’m considering a class name mismatch since our test loads from a different classpath. The dynamic access filter might ignore tests that directly call the compiler-generated class$ method. I might explore Groovy's MetaClass for invocation.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Questioning coverage rules**\\n\\nI’m considering whether the coverage infrastructure has a special rule that excludes direct calls to Class.forName from being counted. It might be that the closure class's class$ method isn't part of the effective instrumented classes in JaCoCo. Even if it's in the rest_assured jar, the dynamic-access report instrumenter could be rewriting those call sites. This makes me think that if it's invoked through MethodHandles, it may not register the original native Class.forName call properly.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCal